          "body": "When Jesus asks *are you able to drink the cup that I am about to drink?* (20:22), He is reaching into a deep OT image. The cup is repeatedly the cup of God's wrath poured out on sin (Psalm 75:8; Isaiah 51:17, 22; Jeremiah 25:15-28; Ezekiel 23:31-34). At Gethsemane this same cup will press Jesus to bloody sweat (26:39, 42) — not because death is fearful in itself, but because the cup is the wrath-bearing portion of substitution. James and John, knowing little of this, answer *we are able* (20:22). Jesus does not correct their boldness; He affirms it (*my cup you shall drink*) — James will be martyred (Acts 12:2), John will endure exile (Revelation 1:9). Disciples do drink a derivative cup of suffering. But the wrath-bearing cup is the Son's alone, and on it the gospel hangs."
