          "title": "*Lutron anti pollon* — the ransom for many",
          "body": "Matthew 20:28 is the chapter's theological summit and one of the New Testament's clearest atonement statements from Jesus' own lips. Four words bear the weight: *give* (His life is given, not taken), *life* (*psuche* — His very self), *ransom* (*lutron* — the redemption-price for a captive), and *for many* (*anti pollon* — substitutionary preposition, *in place of* many). The phrase fuses Isaiah 53:10-12 (the Servant gives Himself as a guilt-offering for many) with the LXX redemption-vocabulary of Exodus 21:30 and Leviticus 25. Jesus interprets His own coming death: it is not martyrdom, not example, not tragedy — it is **purchase**. He pays a price; captives go free. The *many* is not less than all who believe; it is the multitude of those for whom the ransom is effectually applied (cf. Isaiah 53:11; Revelation 5:9). The chapter that opened with workers calculating wages closes with the Master paying the price they could never pay."
