          "title": "Two blind men see what the Twelve still miss",
          "body": "The chapter ends not with discourse but with a dramatized parable in flesh. Two blind beggars sit by the Jericho road as the pilgrim crowd surges past. They cry *Lord, Son of David, have mercy on us!* (20:30) — confessing the messianic title that the Twelve have grasped in word (16:16) but resist in shape. The crowd tells them to be silent; they cry out *all the more* (20:31). Jesus stops, asks the same question He asked the Zebedee mother (*what do you want / wish?*, 20:21, 32) — and the answer this time is not *thrones* but *that our eyes be opened*. He is *moved with compassion* (*splagchnizomai*), touches them, and *immediately they regained their sight and followed Him* (20:34). The chapter that began with workers grumbling ends with beggars seeing. The chapter that began with calculations ends with mercy. The chapter that announced *the last shall be first* ends with the last — two unnamed roadside beggars — becoming the first to follow the Son of David up the final hill."
